From a global health surveillance perspective, merging and re‐emerging infectious diseases will continue to pose a threat to mankind, and it is necessary to develop an arsenal of tools that can be utilized in combatting these pathogens with epidemic/pandemic potential. Based on historical experience, the next big outbreak will be something we have not seen before. In February 2018, The World Health Organization (WHO) added to the R&D Blueprint list of priority of diseases, Disease X. [
47
] Clade X was previously considered a hypothetical variant of an existing family of organisms that evolved to cause human disease. A preparedness exercise using this modelled pandemic‐causing pathogen demonstrated that a lack of actionable interventions could cause devastating global outcomes. [
